Robotics program came out of our productivity 
program. The industrial engineering department

00:07.941 --> 00:18.391
is now involved in an Air Force effort to set up an 
artificial intelligence program.

00:19.352 --> 00:29.903
And a lot of the advanced manufacturing system 
work that is currently being done by Dr. Don

00:19.352 --> 00:29.903
Phillips and others in industrial engineering 
had its roots in the Park Community. And so,

00:34.643 --> 00:47.034
although it does not exist as such now, it laid the 
foundation for some activities that are

00:34.643 --> 00:47.034
currently going on. And incidentally, here 
again, the only reason that that thing succeeded

00:47.154 --> 00:59.586
was that Mr. Jensen and Mr. Whitmore gave me a chunk 
of TEE's money with which to promote them. And

01:02.866 --> 01:05.549
that's the only thing we did. And if I can tell you 
just a quick story about that thing. Dr. Ray

01:13.198 --> 01:24.911
Goforth, who at that time was in industrial 
engineering, but now is in mechanical

01:13.198 --> 01:24.911
engineering, and is a very confident guy. One 
summer, using T's money, we pursued this problem

01:28.962 --> 01:50.514
of why weren't numerically controlled machines 
showing up, particularly in what we call the

01:28.962 --> 01:50.514
mom-and-pop machine shops, the little job shops 
that, again, dot the back alleys

01:28.962 --> 01:50.514
of Houston and Dallas and other large cities. And 
don't misunderstand, they're not always just

01:50.574 --> 01:54.941
real small operations. Some of those things are 
really small. And so with T's money, we did a study

01:58.932 --> 02:09.728
of the barriers to the utilization of numerically 
controlled machines in small shops. It turned out

02:11.491 --> 02:17.800
to have been a mere classic. And gave us 
credibility that led to research activities,

02:17.820 --> 02:26.593
research sponsorship. And this is, again, you 
see, the thing that you have to do. You can't take an

02:32.728 --> 02:44.180
outfit that has no track record in a given area and 
go to a sponsor and say, here, give me some money to

02:32.728 --> 02:44.180
do some work in that area. He's going to say, well, 
what the hell have you done? And quite improperly

02:47.123 --> 02:48.304
so. And if you say, well, nothing, but if you give us 
some money, we're going to do something great.

02:55.451 --> 02:56.192
That ain't going to get it. And so we, the money that 
we got from the National Science Foundation came

02:56.678 --> 03:20.131
out of a, really came out of that little study that 
Ray Goforth did for us back in the summer of 76, I

02:56.678 --> 03:20.131
think, 76, I can't remember.

03:23.956 --> 03:25.318
And it led to an exchange that i had with a guy from 
the national science foundation because they had

03:25.619 --> 03:54.681
a productivity program at that time and and the 
interesting thing that came out of our study was

03:25.619 --> 03:54.681
that the reason people weren't using these 
advanced manufacturing systems was because they

03:25.619 --> 03:54.681
were afraid of them they didn't understand they 
didn't understand what they could what these

03:25.619 --> 03:54.681
devices could do for them and they were afraid of 
what they might do to them. And Ray's work that

03:59.968 --> 04:09.737
summer, and he had a couple of students work on it, I 
thought was magnificent. And it brought that

04:10.538 --> 04:12.980
forth very clearly. Well,

04:13.020 --> 04:24.550
as it so happened, I went to a meeting sponsored by 
the National Science Foundation dealing with

04:13.020 --> 04:24.550
productivity matters, and they got into this very 
issue. Their view, traditional Bank of the

04:26.268 --> 04:33.675
Potomac's myopia, was that it all rested on money. 
If these people just had money, they would go buy

04:33.695 --> 04:40.242
these machines and use them and so forth. Well, 
hell, it was obvious that the people in Houston, I

04:40.542 --> 04:52.214
mean, most of them tied to the petrochemical 
industry making machine parts for them, they were

04:40.542 --> 04:52.214
laughing all the way at the bank. I mean, money was 
anything but a problem. And so, as a matter of fact,

04:56.727 --> 05:08.478
in this public meeting up in Rochester, New York, I 
got into another heated discussion with this guy

04:56.727 --> 05:08.478
from the National Science Foundation, who was a 
friend, Jose Isma. And so, you know, I told him,

05:08.678 --> 05:13.703
we've got data to dispute that. And so he said, I 
want to see that. And so he did see it, and that led to

05:16.005 --> 05:24.473
our, well, it led to a lot of things. We eventually 
got involved in the Air Force's ICAM program, the

05:25.347 --> 05:38.378
Integrated Computer Engineering Manufacturing 
Program, largely because they were concerned

05:25.347 --> 05:38.378
about technology transfer. Because of this 
little rigging study that we had done, we're sort

05:38.915 --> 05:47.584
of nationally recognized experts on technology 
transfer. But it's just an indication, again, of

05:48.825 --> 05:55.733
the power of just a little bit of tease winning. And 
again, if it hadn't been there, we wouldn't have

05:55.753 --> 05:59.256
done it. Let's go back to the flight mode. Oh, okay. 
Okay,

