back to the 60s then.

06:14.911 --> 06:33.070
Well, of course I had naturally when I came here in 
64, having been involved in hypersonic and

06:14.911 --> 06:33.070
reentry research associated with the space 
program at that time, and I don't think, you know,

06:14.911 --> 06:33.070
at that time we couldn't We couldn't foresee that 
as soon as the Apollo program had been successful

06:34.231 --> 06:47.144
that everything was going to go downhill. We 
thought that investing in space-type research

06:47.224 --> 06:55.914
was a heck of a good thing to do. So I was obviously 
interested in promoting that when I came down

06:56.414 --> 07:03.141
here. And I was primarily an experimentalist. I 
hadn't done a lot of theoretical work. It was

07:12.100 --> 07:18.170
mostly wind tone work and making measurements and 
stuff. Of course, we didn't have a hypersonic

07:18.190 --> 07:23.238
facility here. And so it seemed as though that the 
most inexpensive facility that we could develop

07:23.258 --> 07:30.850
was a shotgun. which is a device that will create 
hypersonic flows for very, very short periods of

07:31.218 --> 07:41.613
time. And basically you have this large tube and 
you create a very high pressure shock wave which

07:41.633 --> 07:57.495
rushes down the tube and pulls the air

07:41.633 --> 07:57.495
behind it, with it, at very high speeds. And so you 
can do some good work. Back in those days, of

08:02.441 --> 08:17.939
course, the work that needed to be done was very 
basic work

08:02.441 --> 08:17.939
because aerodynamics was in a completely new 
realm. Normally, of course, air is nitrogen and

08:18.820 --> 08:26.689
oxygen, N2 and O2, both diatomic molecules, 
principally. Those molecules, in addition to

08:27.125 --> 08:39.319
bouncing off one another like billiard balls, the 
individual atoms in the molecule vibrate. There

08:39.379 --> 08:47.989
is an intermolecular bond based on largely the 
electronic attraction that holds them together.

08:48.010 --> 08:56.980
But when you talk about a re-entry theory, kind of 
whistling back into the atmosphere at very, very

08:48.010 --> 08:56.980
high speeds, it has a shockwave effect. there's a 
temperature

08:57.668 --> 09:03.955
jump across that shockwave. There's a 
temperature jump across any shockwave, even

09:04.015 --> 09:12.543
though it might be, you know, if you have a Mach 2 
fighter or a Concorde, you know, anything. But

09:12.644 --> 09:24.556
when you talk about Mach 2 or Mach 20, the 
temperature jump is so great that it causes those

09:12.644 --> 09:24.556
molecules, those atoms to, causes the molecules 
to dissociate. And so you have a chemical reaction

09:27.284 --> 09:28.946
The M2 becomes 2N. The same thing for oxygen. So 
this air, or this gas behind the shockwave is no

09:32.912 --> 09:37.298
longer air. It's some weird new gas. And the fact 
that that structure has changed

09:42.585 --> 09:54.321
makes it, made it very difficult to predict the 
lift and drag of things like the Mercury capsule.

09:54.790 --> 10:03.625
If you recall the early Mercury flights, some of 
them, there was one, who flew that? I can't

10:03.645 --> 10:03.986
remember. I think it was the third flight. The guy 
landed miles from the touchdown point. And the

10:12.060 --> 10:20.494
principal reason there was, of course, he was 
flying it at somewhat the wrong angle of attack

10:12.060 --> 10:20.494
from the back end. But nonetheless, our inability 
to predict lift and drag was very great. largely

10:31.173 --> 10:49.838
because we just didn't understand this strange 
new, the ionization blackout, you know, where

10:31.173 --> 10:49.838
even though the temperatures were so high that the 
electrons would peel off of these atoms and create

10:31.173 --> 10:49.838
this sheath of ions behind it, and the radio wave 
wouldn't penetrate it. So we had that ionization

10:49.858 --> 10:54.144
blackout period here and there. All of that stuff 
at that time was, God, that was just, that was way

10:54.164 --> 11:00.032
out stuff. And so shock tubes could create shock 
waves strong enough to cause those chemical

11:00.822 --> 11:08.613
reactions. And so we could study them. And so, 
again, good old teams and good old Harry Whitmore

11:11.137 --> 11:28.162
gave me,

11:11.137 --> 11:28.162
I can't remember, I think it was $40,000 or $50,000 
or something to build a shock tube. And we did. And

11:29.695 --> 11:47.722
again, that was the foundation for some research 
work, which, again, simply would not have

11:29.695 --> 11:47.722
happened had we not gotten that money for teams. 
Well, so the shock tube lab, and we had a building

11:47.742 --> 11:55.733
given to us out at the annex. It wasn't much of a 
building. but it worked out extremely well.

12:06.761 --> 12:12.067
And then, too, we had another strange event 
happen. About 65 or 66, some

12:12.087 --> 12:27.985
students came to me and said, well, the 
traditional areas of activity or specialization

12:12.087 --> 12:27.985
within of aerospace engineering are 
aerodynamics, which has to do with the flow of air

12:28.387 --> 12:46.927
about these mines, structures, making them 
strong enough but light enough to be built by, and

12:28.387 --> 12:46.927
propulsion, which deals with engines and power 
plants, and that sort of thing. But the fourth area

12:46.947 --> 12:55.997
is flight mechanics, which deals with the entire 
vehicle, and it deals with stability and control

12:46.947 --> 12:55.997
and performance. maneuverability and that sort 
of thing. And so some students came to me and said

13:00.738 --> 13:09.109
they were interested

13:00.738 --> 13:09.109
more in flight mechanics. Wasn't there anything 
we could do to get active in that area? Well,

13:14.335 --> 13:25.849
here we were with a beautiful facility, the old 
Bryan Air Force Base, parallel 7,500 foot

13:25.964 --> 13:40.057
runways, but at

13:25.964 --> 13:40.057
that time they had courses. To me, being one who has 
been put on airplanes

13:40.077 --> 13:54.030
for many years, I think the saddest thing that one 
can see is an abandoned airplane, an airplane as a

13:54.736 --> 14:18.413
relic, you know, that's

13:54.736 --> 14:18.413
just uncared for, sitting

13:54.736 --> 14:18.413
on the corner

13:54.736 --> 14:18.413
of an airport or in a hangar

13:54.736 --> 14:18.413
and just, you know, falling. And, you know, I think 
that at one time it was a, it must have been a

14:18.433 --> 14:20.356
beautiful sight in flight. And there it sits, 
rusting and deteriorating. The second saddest

14:21.298 --> 14:22.600
thing I think it's an abandoned airport.

14:27.296 --> 14:32.881
Well, you can imagine that all the times there were 
great and wonderful things that happened in the

14:27.296 --> 14:32.881
past. People learning to fly. Now it's just a cow 
pasture, or in that case, a horse pasture. And they

14:43.973 --> 14:49.519
had hangers out there that were just unused. And so 
I thought, well, gosh, maybe we could do something

14:52.043 --> 14:57.088
with that facility. Now, there was another 
thought that entered my mind at that time, and that

14:58.048 --> 15:12.622
was that we had gotten the wind tunnel, the big wind 
tunnel, back in operation, and we were working

14:58.048 --> 15:12.622
there. And it occurred to me that if we could have a 
flight lab, that that would give us a very powerful

15:12.642 --> 15:20.869
combination. We could not only do wind tunnel 
tests, but we could take the results of those tests

15:21.035 --> 15:33.706
and flight test them, put them actually on an 
airplane, you see. And the number of

15:33.727 --> 15:41.754
institutions, universities that had that 
capability were very, very limited. Count them

15:42.575 --> 15:46.638
easily on a finger in one hand. And so I thought it 
just might lead to something good. Well, here

15:52.557 --> 16:04.611
again, thank God for Aggie students and their 
unbelievable enthusiasm. And thank God for Key's

16:04.631 --> 16:08.154
money. Because, again, I went to Harry Whitmore 
and laid the idea before him. And I have to tell you

16:13.601 --> 16:21.990
here,

16:13.601 --> 16:21.990
I don't think I have ever gone to Harry Whitmore and 
said, I need this.

16:27.209 --> 16:32.756
And that's, you know, that's just, that's 
unbelievable. I mean, that's incredible.

16:38.343 --> 16:43.289
But in any event, he said, yeah, let's pursue that. 
And so he gave me a little bit of money with which I

16:43.309 --> 16:50.578
could hire some students.

